Let's think step by step. Given the problem statement, since $a=0$ results in $x^4 - x^2 + 1 = 0,$ for which there is no solution, we see that $a > 0.$ We claim that there is no solution when $a\geq2$ as well. To show this, note that plugging in $x=1/2$ into the polynomial yields $$\frac{1}{16}+\frac{a}{8}-\frac{b}{4}+\frac{a}{2}+1$$which reduces to$$-\frac{7}{16}+\frac{9a}{8}-\frac{b}{4}=0.$$Rearranging terms, we get $$\frac{-7+9a-b}{4}=0,$$ so $-7+9a-b=0$, implying that $b=9a-7$. Substituting this into the original equation and simplifying yields \begin{align*}
x^4 + ax^3 - (9a-7)x^2 + ax + 1 &= 0\\
x^4 + ax^3 - 9ax^2 + 7x^2
